I stapled the shit out of them until they were puffy and weird, like muscles filled with blood. Then I covered them with jewels. Didn’t sell a lot of them. Most people thought ‘What the fuck are these?’ At the opening of the show I noticed two women talking quietly to each other: one of them was full-figured, the other one was old. So I decided to eavesdrop. And they must have gone to art school, because I heard the big one say: ‘Look at these, they’re so beautiful. But they do nothing.’ I never went to art school, so I thought ‘Oh shit, they found out how stupid I am.’ It made me feel so dumb. When I was a kid I had a big head, a football head. I had to wear a helmet. And this woman gave me that ‘football head feeling’ all over again. I wanted to slug her. I wanted to scream: ‘My art does nothing? What the fuck is it supposed to do, vacuum your house?’ But my mother taught me to never burn a bridge. So instead of blowing it out my mouth, I took a deep breath. I said to myself: ‘Just wait, wait a minute. Gestate with negative things, like a shaman. Like a little magic man.’ I said to myself: ‘Maybe they’re right. Wouldn’t it be great if my paintings could do something?’ A few weeks later I ended up finding an old man named Carl who has a hoard of crystals that he sells by the pound. All of Carl’s crystals have healing ‘goo goo’ in them, so I bought $5,000 worth. You see? By holding my tongue, I got something. Those women gave me a gift with their bitchery. They’ll meet with embarrassment. They’ll meet their inner critic. They’ll have moments where they think: that’s too loud, that’s too shrill. But they have to push past it. grow into something like this? I think it’s because people are tired of ‘connecting’ through screens. Nobody wants to live in a metaverse, whatever the hell that is. We don’t want to become passive consumers of songs that ‘seem’ human, art that ‘seems’ human, friends that ‘seem’ human. None of this stuff is what we need. We need to create. We need to connect. We need to serve other people if we’re going to have any sort of place or belonging in this world. If humanity is going to thrive— and if art is going to thrive – there is only one place for it to go: the real world. Dear New York was founded upon the increasingly rare belief that humanity is pretty freaking amazing. This isn’t a perfect world. Every day the media brings us new examples of glaring injustice and senseless violence. We still have much work to do. But while we do the work, let us not forget how much love there is in this world. In New York City alone, in a single day, there are millions of stories of people taking care of each other. These stories don’t make the evening news, but they’re no less real. And when you sum it all up—the good and the bad – humanity is still worth fighting for. It’s still something to celebrate. 'username': 'dumbo_brooklyn'}], 'isCommentsDisabled': False}, {'id': '3745582128756237406', 'type': 'Sidecar', 'shortCode': 'DP6-xnlkSRe', 'caption': 'Last night someone asked me what part of Dear New York I’m proudest of; this was hard to answer. But I can tell you what’s filled my heart the most. Many in the press are calling it ‘The Children’s Exhibit,’ because Dear New York’s Vanderbilt Hall features the work of six hundred NYC student artists. Each student was asked to photograph and write about someone who has made a difference in their lives. Some of these artists are as young as four, and their photography might not be the most technically polished, but there is a striking intimacy that can only come from photographing someone you love. The written profiles which accompany the photographs are extremely touching, and collectively represent the millions of invisible, unsung heroes that form the bedrock of NYC’s community. It’s not the mayors and the movie stars that form the heart of this city. It’s the mothers, the fathers, the teachers, the social workers, and the millions of other people who show up every day in the lives of others. One reason the ‘Children’s Exhibit’ lands so deeply is that its amplified by a sister exhibition featuring eleven highly notable NYC photographers. Among them are living legends such as @jamelshabazz , a trailblazer in street portraiture. As well as Gugenheim Fellow @sarabennettbrooklyn , a former public defender who profiles formerly-incarcerated women. The two exhibits are blended seamlessly in an innovative, immersive design by @davidkorins . The most beautiful part of these blended exhibits is that all 611 artists— young and old, beginning and established— have been given the same museum-quality framing and presentation. The result is an egalitarian, non-hierarchical ode to the diversity, humanity, and community of this city.  The exhibit has been overflowing all week, from open to close, and I’m not sure I’ve ever seen an art installation elicit so much emotion. Dear New York closes on Sunday. If you come by subway, you’ll enter through an immersive installation covering all three levels of Grand Central subway station, designed by @trabuccocampos and his team at @pentagramdesign. You’ll then emerge into an iconic main concourse which has been completely transformed with light projections into a showcase of NYC’s humanity. For the first time in history, the main concourse has also been transformed by two weeks of musical programming performed by the celebrated students and alumni of @juilliardschool . After taking in a performance, be sure to swing by Vanderbilt Hall to experience the most-visited, most-talked-about art exhibit in town, designed by the legendary @davidkorins , and featuring the work of eleven highly notable NYC photographers alongside the work of 600 school-aged student artists—every participant given the same museum-quality printing and framing by @pictonewyork .  At 8 PM on Sunday night, there will be a short closing ceremony featuring a performance by a 200-strong chorus from @ypcofnyc. Afterwards Dear New York will go dark forever. I’d never heard of him. He had about 30,000 Twitter followers at the time. He’d created a critically acclaimed show called ‘In The Heights,’ but I wasn’t fluent enough with Broadway for that to ring a bell. In his DM he told me to ‘holler’ at him if I ever came up to Washington Heights. A few weeks later, that’s exactly what I did. Why? Because I needed a Spanish interpreter, and I wanted to know if he’d consider accompanying me while I collected stories. Lin informed me that this would not be possible, because he’d just come home from the hospital with his newborn son. ‘Oh, really?’ I asked. And that’s how I randomly took the first portrait of the brand-new Miranda family. Lin mentioned at the time that he was working on ‘some play about Alexander Hamilton.’ Four months later Hamilton would have its off-Broadway premiere at the Public Theater. And well, the rest is history. I’ve always treasured this small intersection I had with Lin before the rocket ship took off. Not because I got to watch him change. But because I got to watch how little he changed. He’s remained the same good man I met that day: enamored with his newborn son, enamored with his wife, enamored with life. He’s gone on to compose music for so many celebrated films, modeling that zest for life to millions of children around the world— including my own. (I’m a Moana man myself, with all due respect to the Family Madrigal.) But what I’ve most admired about Lin is how much he supports other people. I’m not sure I’ve ever seen someone use their platform to so consistently highlight and uplift fellow artists. In that vein, he immediately agreed when I asked if he’d drop by Dear New York to play the Steinway Concert Grand. He spent days trying to lower my expectations. ‘I’m not a pianist,’ he said. ‘All I can do is noodle on the keys.’ And that’s exactly what he did this morning. He ‘noodled’ his way into the memories and lives of hundreds of very surprised people in Grand Central Station. Thank you @lin_manuel , for always reaching behind you to lift others up. Only recently did I discover its existence. It was a very unusual DM—especially coming from a local assemblyman who would soon be running for higher office. He had very little name recognition at the time, and could have benefited from publicity. But unlike the thousands of messages I’ve received from people with something to promote, Zohran did not ask to be featured on Humans of New York. Instead he asked if he could introduce me to taxi drivers that were struggling beneath the burden of debt. Coming from a man with political ambitions, this self-denying request was so strange as to be almost singular. I don’t endorse politicians on Humans of New York. But I’ll endorse a good man. And it was a good man who cleared 30 minutes from his schedule yesterday to swing by Grand Central to visit Dear New York. Nearly fifty student artists were visiting that day with their families, and I thought a surprise visit from this widely-loved future mayor would be a special memory for all of them. Before Zohran’s arrival I was convinced I’d made a terrible mistake. The Vanderbilt Hall exhibit was filled to capacity with adult visitors. Dear New York is self-funded so there was very little staff and security for crowd control. In the crush of people I was almost certain this special day for the kids would devolve into thirty minutes of selfie requests. But everyone rose to the occasion. Hundreds of adults quickly cleared the room and stood outside the exhibit. Eleven very notable adult artists are also featured in the exhibition, but even they took a step back, so that these students could briefly have the stage to themselves. Each child stood by their work and Zohran was able to meet all of them, one at a time, and honor their contributions to the most-visited art show in New York City. Thanks to everyone who ceded the stage yesterday to make this moment possible. Thank you Zohran for literally sitting down on the floor so that these young artists could feel so tall. Thank you for continually centering other people in your life and work.
